text: Reading "Master and Commander" it seems while sailing in the 18th century you would just randomly encounter Algerian pirate ships & when you had to fight them they would be full of Christian slaves chained to the oars that you'd be killing if you fired at them... Very Mordor-ish.

A friend of mine produced a wonderful essay this year about the legal history of piracy and how it was considered that pirates are at a perpetual state of war with mankind so treating them very harshly was permitted... Hope he makes it public soon to share here.

Shashlik in its current form was invented by French chefs in Russia in the 19th century even though it's considered Caucasian traditional cuisine. Stuff like Weston Price talking about Scottish islanders eating cod's head stuffed with oatmeal is what much food looked like before.

I wonder if a potential "'Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?' guy" who is obsessed with the show and watches all previous seasons from the TV archives, purchases companion books, etc. will be perfect candidate to win or it will be completely useless as they do not repeat questions...

He watches translated episodes from the Vietnamese, Finnish, and German versions, has all the quizbooks in his library, has seen every season of the show available anywhere, etc. He knows what to expect... But what if his knowledge is a perfect silhouette around the challenge...

Weren't the Hobbit movies filmed in 48 fps, double the normal 24 fps frame rate of 99.9% of films? I remember there was a huge discussion on computer forums back in the day about it. Pretty sure it's like watching a stream of a video game so it's an apt choice for the occasion...

No one has mentioned it in the comments so I think I'm the only one who remembers this, it was a big debate on the 2010s internet, some people said watching them made them feel nauseous, others thought it was a cultural limitation and in the future all films would be 144 fps...
It's 48 according to google but I was also unsure and thought it might have been 60
No it makes sense because regular films are 24 so it's just double that, we're just mixing it up with 30 fps vs 60 fps in video games back in the day I think

Someone said it felt like "being on a theme park ride instead of watching a movie", I like the description. The concept itself sounds very brave to me, even if it failed. It's like what the Valve Corporation under Gabe Newell would do if they were tasked with producing a film.

Dmitry Galkovsky had a really fun quote about how one day there will be huge spaceships traveling between galaxies through space and still in the super futuristic spaceship in the utility room in the place of honor there will be a regular hammer. A hammer will always be a hammer.
